{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17412784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17412784"},"attributes":{"position":14,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16849"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563688"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:03:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:03:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16849"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261074"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:38:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:40:20+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":19,"questionsAnswered":7,"marksTotal":19,"marksAttainable":7,"marksAttempted":7,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:39:59+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.14,"questionsCorrect":1,"marksCorrect":1},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"16849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16849"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.07,0.16,0.06,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9539"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67306"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9539"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16849"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52758"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"2451"},{"type":"tags","id":"4412"},{"type":"tags","id":"4434"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22536"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67306"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Labour Ward in active labour at 39 weeks gestation. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is receiving an oxytocin infusion for augmentation of labour. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The midwife describes palpating five to six strong contractions every 10 minutes with little resting tone between the contractions. The cardiotocograph shows a baseline fetal heart rate of 140 beats per minute with no accelerations and reduced baseline variability. The fetal heart rate suddenly drops to 80 beats per minute for two minutes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fetal scalp blood sampling","Administration of terbutaline","Emergency caesarean section","Continue current management with close observation","Cease oxytocin infusion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes fetal deceleration (heart rate less than 110 beats per minute) in the context of uterine hyperstimulation, which is defined as excessive uterine activity (more than five contractions in 10 minutes, contractions lasting longer than two minutes, or contractions occurring prior to the return to baseline tone).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECease oxytocin infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step as it directly addresses the cause of the fetal compromise. Oxytocin increases both frequency and strength of uterine contractions, and its immediate cessation can allow for normalisation of uterine activity and improvement in fetal oxygenation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFetal scalp blood sampling\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate during an acute deceleration as it would delay definitive management and may not provide useful information during an acute event.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministration of terbutaline\u003C/strong\u003E, a tocolytic agent, may be considered if the deceleration persists despite stopping the oxytocin. However, it is not the first step in management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmergency caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if the fetal deceleration persists beyond 5 minutes despite conservative measures, but it is not the first-line management. Initial steps should focus on reversing the cause of the bradycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue current management with close observation\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as active intervention is required to address the fetal deceleration. Additional supportive measures should include positioning the mother in left lateral position and administering supplemental oxygen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Uterine hyperstimulation can cause fetal bradycardia and requires immediate cessation of oxytocin.","Left lateral positioning and oxygen supplementation are supportive measures in fetal bradycardia.","Tocolytics may be required if bradycardia persists despite conservative measures."],"references":["Hope A. The fetal bradycardia. O\u0026G Magazine [Internet]. 2019 [cited 2024 Dec 4];19(2). Available from: https://www.ogmagazine.org.au/19/2-19/the-fetal-bradycardia/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52758"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16849"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52758"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T19:27:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T19:28:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9539"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67306"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nu